  "response_text": "In black and white, a pair of hands in dark sleeves with light sailor-style stripes sorts through a loose pile of letters, papers, and fabric against a dark background. The hands shuffle envelopes quickly, then single out a small envelope with a postage stamp in the upper right corner. It is held closer, filling the view. The address is written in flowing cursive and appears to be for “Mr. Jack Hudson” aboard a U.S. ship, with “F.P.O. San Francisco, Calif.” on the lower lines.\n\nThe envelope gives way to a close view of a letter being written. A hand with neatly manicured, dark-polished nails holds a fountain pen and writes in large, slanted cursive on a sheet of paper. Several lines of handwriting are already on the page, and the writer adds more at the lower right, including a closing that appears to read “Love, Peggy.” The paper is lifted and held in both hands, the cursive filling much of the page. Over the handwritten letter, a soft, ghostlike image of a young woman’s face appears, as if her presence is being imagined through the words.\n\nThe scene shifts to another letter being written on a pad resting on a light-colored cushion or pillow. The writer’s sleeves again have sailor-style stripes, suggesting a naval uniform. One hand steadies the paper while the other writes with a fountain pen, adding lines beneath a block of already-written text. Beside the writing surface, a framed portrait appears: a young man in a sailor uniform and white sailor cap, facing forward with a calm expression. A woman’s manicured hand touches the glass of the portrait, sliding gently over the man’s face and pausing near his mouth, as though responding tenderly to the image. The portrait remains beside the writing for a moment, then the view returns to the sailor’s hands continuing to write on the page.\n\nThe commercial then focuses closely on the pen itself. A large, detailed view of the fountain pen point fills the screen, showing the shiny nib and the feed beneath it. A very thin tube extends forward from the pen point, past the nib. The pen is then shown above an open ink bottle. The bottle mouth is seen from above, with dark ink inside, while the slender tube reaches down into the ink. The nib remains above the ink, visually demonstrating that only the tube dips in. The pen is lifted away, and the attention shifts to the rounded top of the pen cap or barrel, where a small bright circular emblem—the Sheaffer white dot—is set above a shiny clip. The white dot grows larger until it nearly fills the view.\n\nInside a circular transition from the white dot, a hand is again shown writing on a sheet of paper laid on a tabletop. The pen is a smooth, streamlined fountain pen, held in a right hand with a light shirt cuff visible. The handwritten lines on the page include the phrase “When it comes to writing” and “come to Sheaffer’s,” repeated or continued as the hand writes. Large white script lettering appears over the writing hand, spelling “Writing” across the lower half of the screen. Finally, bold block capital letters reading “SHEAFFER’S” appear across the center, superimposed over the hand as it continues to write.",
